[2] UK (Scotland)
Date: Wed 28 Nov 2012
Source: Wishaw Press [edited]
http://www.wishawpress.co.uk/wishaw-news/local-wishaw-news/wishaw-news/2012/11/28/nhs-lanarkshire-confirm-measles-outbreak-among-young-people-in-newmains-76495-32319067/


Health bosses have written to dozens of parents in Newmains after a measles outbreak in the village. NHS [National Health Service] Lanarkshire sent messages last week to the parents of pupils at Newmains Nursery Centre and Morningside Primary. In both Newmains and Larkhall, there are now 12 confirmed and one suspected case of the infectious disease. The children and young people affected are currently recovering at home.

Health officials wrote to all of the parents to inform them of the situation and offer advice and MMR vaccine for some children and young people. However, it emerged that over 94 per cent of the youngsters have already had at least one MMR treatment already.

NHS Lanarkshire's health protection team have been responding to the outbreak. Dr David Cromie, consultant in public health medicine and a member of the response team, spoke to the Wishaw Press about the outbreak. He said: "Although the cases caught measles in their own communities, some of them have attended local schools and could spread the illness to others. As such, we have written to the parents of pupils at Newmains Nursery Centre, Morningside Primary in Newmains and Larkhall Academy to inform them of the situation and offer health advice and MMR vaccine for some children and young people. MMR (measles-mumps-rubella) vaccination provides good individual protection against measles, and a high uptake rate in a social group helps prevent measles from spreading. So, it is very encouraging that over 94 per cent of children attending these schools have had at least one dose of MMR. However, we are recommending that all children should have at least one dose of MMR, and those who are over 3 years 4 months of age should have 2 doses of MMR vaccine."

Dr Cromie continued: "Those who would benefit from MMR vaccine are being offered the jab by public health nurses. Measles used to be a common disease of childhood but is currently rare. It is a very infectious disease caused by a virus. It is spread from person to person by sneezing and coughing. Most people who get measles get a fever, rash, runny nose, sore throat -- with white spots in the mouth -- and cough. They can feel quite unwell for a week and usually recover completely within a few weeks, but for some, it can be very severe and even life threatening. If anyone is concerned that they or their children may have measles, they should contact their GP."

[Byline: Robert Mitchell]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Wishaw is a town and former burgh in North Lanarkshire, Scotland. It is on the edge of the Clyde Valley. A map showing the location of North Lanarkshire can be accessed at: http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2002/08/15279/10311. It is surprising that so many cases are still being recorded in an area where vaccine uptake has reached 94 percent. - Mod.CP

